Domestic violence survivors suffer a range of serious physical and mental health consequences that require urgent health responses and these should be readily available during #COVID19UG #SRHRandCOVID19

1 in 3 women around the world experience physical or sexual violence, mostly by an intimate partner. Statistics show that domestic violence is the most widespread, but among the least reported human rights abuses and these might skyrocket during #COVID19UG #SRHRandCOVID19

Lockdown orders during #COVID19UG also mean that victims of domestic violence are unable to leave the house to seek appropriate help and are more likely to be cut off from their usual support systems. #SRHRandCOVID19

While #Lockdown and #Curfew are crucial measures in helping to flatten the curve, it is inadvertently leading to the rise of another public health issue domestic violence (intimate partner violence) #COVID19UG #SRHRandCOVID19

During crises like #COVID19UG the risk of domestic violence escalates as perpetrators seek to maintain a sense of power and control in their lives. The current pandemic presents a combination of economic and health uncertainties that could spur an increase in domestic violence.
